Let \(E[X] = \mu\). Show that \(Var[X] := E[(X-E[X])^2] = E[X^2]-(E[X])^2\). Note, all you have to do is show the second equality (the first is our definition from class).

\(E[(X-E[X])^2]\) \(E[X^2-((2)(X)(E[X]))+E[X]^2]\) First, I distributed the squared property onto each variable in the parenthesis. \(E[X^2]-E[(2)(X)(E[X])]+E[E[X]^2]\) Next, I distributed the expectation to each section. \(E[X^2]-(2(E[X])(E[X]))+(E[X])^2\) Because of the linearity of expectations, I pulled the constant (2(E[X])) out of the brackets which left me with -(2(E[X])(E[X])). \(E[X^2]-2((E[X])^2)+(E[X])^2\) I simplified further, condensing the middle section to -2((E[X])^2). \(E[X^2]-(E[X])^2\) I combined -2((E[X])^2) and (E[X])^2, which left me with -(E[X])^2.

In the computational section of this homework, we will discuss support vector machines and tree-based methods. I will begin by simulating some data for you to use with SVM.

library(e1071)
set.seed(1) 
x=matrix(rnorm(200*2),ncol=2)
x[1:100,]=x[1:100,]+2
x[101:150,]=x[101:150,]-2
y=c(rep(1,150),rep(2,50))
dat=data.frame(x=x,y=as.factor(y))
plot(x, col=y)

2.1

Quite clearly, the above data is not linearly separable. Create a training-testing partition with 100 random observations in the training partition. Fit an svm on this training data using the radial kernel, and tuning parameters \(\gamma=1\), cost \(=1\). Plot the svm on the training data.

set.seed(1)
train=sample(200,100)
svmfit = svm(y ~ ., data = dat[train,], kernel = "radial", gamma = 1, cost = 1)
plot(svmfit, dat[train,])

2.2

Notice that the above decision boundary is decidedly non-linear. It seems to perform reasonably well, but there are indeed some misclassifications. Letâ€™s see if increasing the cost 1 helps our classification error rate. Refit the svm with the radial kernel, \(\gamma=1\), and a cost of 10000. Plot this svm on the training data.

svmfit = svm(y ~ ., data = dat[train,], kernel = "radial", gamma = 1, cost = 10000)
plot(svmfit, dat[train,])

2.3

It would appear that we are better capturing the training data, but comment on the dangers (if any exist), of such a model.

Increasing the cost(C) can lead to overfitting of the training data, which will then become too specific to be accurate for the testing data. It is important to maintain a balance when deciding the C value for an SVM model. If a smaller C value is resulting in a large number of misclassifications, increasing the C value may help alleviate this. However, you must find a balance. If the C value is too high, it will minimize misclassifications, but the model may be fit too closely to the training data and be unable to accurately predict the testing data. In this example, we increased the C value by 10000%, which is a drastic increase and is likely fit too closely to the testing data, meaning it will be too specific to be accurate when predicting the testing data. There must be a level of margin generality while still maximizing the accuracy of classifications.

Create a confusion matrix by using this svm to predict on the current testing partition. Comment on the confusion matrix. Is there any disparity in our classification results?

Is this disparity because of imbalance in the training/testing partition? Find the proportion of class 2 in your training partition and see if it is broadly representative of the underlying 25% of class 2 in the data as a whole.

sum(dat[train,3] == 2)/100
## [1] 0.29

Since the proportion of class 2 is 29%, which is moderately close to the 25% underlying proportion of actual class 2, it is less likely that the disparity is due to an imbalance in the training/testing partition. Most likely, the cost(C) variable was too high and led to overfitting of the data. Since overfitting leads to a tight margin and more emphasis on accuracy, it is likely that the model was unable to accurately predict the testing data because the model was too closely fit to the training data. In order to alleviate this, the C value should be decreased and an ideal combination of gamma and C values should be determined to maintain accuracy while avoiding overfitting the data. However, the model may remain bias even when the training data is representative because of the abnormal decision boundary.

3.5

Discuss the trade-off in accuracy and interpretability in pruning the above tree.

After pruning the tree, the error rate changed from 19.3% to 24.6%. Pruning the tree decreases the â€˜purityâ€™ of the data, but allows the data to generalize well and results in a more representative training set. If the tree isnâ€™t pruned, it will increase the accuracy rate, but it will result in overfitting of the data and decrease the interpretability in the data set. Pruning only the unnecessary branches towards to bottom will create a balance between accurarcy and interpretability. The branches that remain (thal, ca, cp) are the most signifigant branches for the data set, which is why they remain after the pruning process. Sacrificing a percentage of accuracy is vital when ensuring that the data is interpretable, generalized, and provides a representative training set. ##

Discuss the ways a decision tree could manifest algorithmic bias.

A large factor in decision trees is the balance between variance and bias. If the tree is too complex and left unpruned, the bias will be low, but the variance will be high and can lead to overfitting of the data. In contrast, if the tree is overly pruned, the variance will be lower, but the bias will be much higher, creating a flawed prediction algorithm. When considering the COMPAS algorithmic bias, an unpruned tree could have contributed to the bias outcomes. If the tree was pruned too much in hopes of decreasing the variance and increasing accuracy, the bias would be high, leading to algorithmic bias. It is likely that the creators of COMPAS did not find the proper balance between bias and variance and instead, (hopefully unknowingly) sacrificed a crucial branch (or branches) that decreased racial bias in favor of creating a maximally accurate algorithm. The presence of too much bias in the outcomes led to ethical issues, specifically with unfair classification based on race. The COMPAS algorithm demonstrates the importance of finding the proper balance when utilizing decision trees. The present issue with the algorithm - significant bias - resulted in flawed, unjust predictions when deciding if inmates were likely to commit crimes upon their release. The racial bias was caused by an overgeneralized data training set. However, the algorithm would also not be reliable if the bias was the only factor considered. The racial bias would be prevented, but the data would be too general to accurately predict whether inmates were likely to commit crimes upon release. Either of the extremes are dangerous for different reasons, demonstrating the need for meticulous balance when using decision trees for prediction, especially on topics as sensitive as this.
